Having just wrapped up how network identities are built (IP Addressing) and handed out (DHCP), I am now moving into how they are actually found. I am dedicating this log to DNS.
Instead of forcing us to memorize IP addresses, DNS works invisibly in the background to resolve domain names to machine-readable numbers. Here is a deep dive into exactly how that
resolution process works.

DNS (Domain Name System): Responsible for resolving names to numbers. More specifically, Domain Names to IP Addresses. So if you type a website name into a search bar, DNS will
resolve that website name into a number, because all computers only speak in numbers.

DNS isn't just a magical translation from names to addresses though, DNS takes steps:
  1. When you type google.com into a web browser, your web browser/OS are going to check in their cache memory to see if they have the IP address. Your OS will check if it has
it anywhere its "Hosts" files or in its DNS cache. If it doesn't it goes to the next level.
  2. If not found in the cache of the device it sends it to the Resolver Server. The Resolver is essentially the ISP and does most of the work when it comes to finding an IP
address. The client is typically not strong enough to communicate with all the higher-level servers to be able to scour the internet for the IP of a website. The process that the
Resolver uses to search for IPs is called "Recursion."
